PHQ-9_1: Are you currently struggling with mental distress? Over the last two weeks, how often have you been bothered by any of the following complaints? - Little interest or pleasure in doing things?
PHQ-9_2: Are you currently struggling with mental distress? Over the last two weeks, how often have you been bothered by any of the following complaints? - Feeling down, depressed, or hopeless?
PHQ-9_3: Are you currently struggling with mental distress? Over the last two weeks, how often have you been bothered by any of the following complaints? - Trouble falling or staying asleep, or sleeping too much?
PHQ-9_4: Are you currently struggling with mental distress? Over the last two weeks, how often have you been bothered by any of the following complaints? - Feeling tired or having little energy?
PHQ-9_5: Are you currently struggling with mental distress? Over the last two weeks, how often have you been bothered by any of the following complaints? - Poor appetite or overeating?
PHQ-9_6: Are you currently struggling with mental distress? Over the last two weeks, how often have you been bothered by any of the following complaints? - Feeling bad about yourself - or that you are a failure or have let yourself or your family down?
PHQ-9_7: Are you currently struggling with mental distress? Over the last two weeks, how often have you been bothered by any of the following complaints? - Trouble concentrating on things, such as reading the newspaper or watching television?
PHQ-9_8: Are you currently struggling with mental distress? Over the last two weeks, how often have you been bothered by any of the following complaints? - Moving or speaking so slowly that other people could have noticed? Or the opposite - being so fidgety or restless that you have been moving around a lot more than usual?
PHQ-9_9: Are you currently struggling with mental distress? Over the last two weeks, how often have you been bothered by any of the following complaints? - Thoughts that you would be better off dead, or of hurting yourself in some way?

Feedback: The graph-based approach, while helpful, also seems a bit risky. While it might make it clear to people at which point in their graph they could start attacking their issues, it might not be that easy to go through with it. Also it might suggest that they could do this without professional help, which seems dangerous in some cases (note that one of examples involved self-harm). Maybe some added suggestion of discussing the graph with a professional for help with further identifying and attacking the root causes might be helpful. Also it somewhat leaves out other categories of root causes outside of the control of the individual (trauma, physical issues etc.).

Feedback: The presentation along with the music was very pleasant. The constant summarization and repetition was perfect. In one of the diagrams in my opinion a node for 'intrusive thoughts' was missing between 'shame' and 'no focus' or should be at least mentioned. Some concepts like arising comorbidities should be mentioned as contributing new emerging factors. A vital point would also be that many use mental distress as excuse for things not going according to plan and start self identifying with it and feel powerless to do anything against it because that bears the risk of being more of a failure and having the excuse is easy and often is only self diagnosed which is highly advised against because of lack of differential diagnosis.
